""
"a great and unique expression of the style here, i love it. paler in color than old ales usually are, without much head from the tap on this one. a nose of sweet layered grain, cinnamon, and sweet oak. even a touch of raisin or dried cherry in here. the flavor is similar, with the toffee grain flavor going from start to finish and the cinnamon and molasses spice unfolding in the middle. dried fruit is more date or fig than berry or cherry on the palate, less sweet. the alcohol is warming, but not cutting or hot, and i think that aspect is really well designed and executed. the spice complexion is really interesting with the lighter colored but full bodied and sticky sweet grain base, it gives it rounder edges and a lingering appeal. a mellow apple cider or mulled character to the finish is really nice, very wintery. enormously satisfying glass of ale here, beautifully done, like nothing else i know."
""
""
""
""
"750 ml bottle into snifter; no bottle dating, but is a recent release. Pours slightly hazy dark reddish brown color with a 1-2 finger dense khaki head with good retention, that reduces to a small cap that lingers. Nice soapy lacing clings around the glass, with a moderate amount of streaming carbonation retaining the head. Aromas of caramel, toast, toffee, brown bread, raisin, cherry, fig, date, brown sugar, chocolate, nuttiness, tannic red wine, vanilla, oak, leather, tobacco, musty funk, herbal, grass, light pepper, and yeast/oak earthiness. Damn nice aromas with good balance and complexity of dark/bready malt, fruity/funky yeast, and oak/cocoa notes; with great strength. Taste of big caramel, toffee, toast, brown bread, raisin, cherry, plum, fig, date, brown sugar, chocolate, nuttiness, tannic red wine, vanilla, oak, leather, tobacco, musty funk, herbal, grass, light pepper, and yeast/oak earthiness. Some light earthy yeast spice and slight tannic tartness on the finish; with lingering notes of caramel, toffee, toast, brown bread, raisin, cherry, plum, fig, date, brown sugar, chocolate, nuttiness, red wine, vanilla, and yeast/oak earthiness on the finish for a while. Incredible complexity, balance, and robustness of dark/bready malt, fruity/funky yeast, and oak/cocoa flavors; with a great yeast/malt/oak balance and zero cloying flavors after the finish. Medium carbonation and medium-full bodied; with a very smooth, fairly creamy, and slightly tart/tannic mouthfeel that is nice. Alcohol is very well hidden with only a slight warming present after the finish. Overall this is an incredible old ale style! All around fantastic complexity and balance of dark/bready malt, fruity/funky yeast, and oak/cocoa flavors; and very smooth to sip on for the big ABV. A highly enjoyable offering."
